8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s unparalleled arts coverage widens the audience for ambitious new art making the funding and work involved go much further</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MIF has found the BBC’s move to Salford to be an extremely positive developme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt for the cultural industries in the North West and beyond</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Manchester International Festival </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is the world’s first festival of original, new work and special events and takes place biennially, in Manchester. The Festival launched in 2007 as an artist-l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed, commissioning festival presenting new works from across the spectrum of performing arts, visual arts and popular culture.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have a wide-ranging and well-established partnership with the BBC, formed over the last eight years – the BBC were a key early</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supporter of MIF and have been involved in every Festival. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As an organization we are interested in the BBC’s remit to stimulate creativity and cultural excellence; this is the purpose that fits most closely with our own, and from our perspective is the a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">im from which all other purposes/outcomes and impacts follow.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a commissioning Festival we have deliberately sought partners who are passionate about creating ambitious new work and are prepared to face the challenges and risks that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">involves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">found the BBC to be a willing and engaged collaborator in the process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC has supported the Festival in numerous ways, providing the time, expertise and talent of many key personnel to help build the commissions themselves, and in excellent, committed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> coverage of Festival events.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have worked with the BBC on several events, notably co-commissioning new work for young audiences, including The Crash</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the Elysium – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">along with groundbreaking theatre company Punchdrunk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and Music Boxes, a melodic adv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enture for children aged 0-3. A highlight of MIF13 was Massive Attack v Adam Curtis, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> iconoclastic film-gig hybrid built around BBC archive footage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; without the BBC’s support this work could not have been made. This show has since played to huge critical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> acclaim in New York’s Park Avenue Armory and Germany’s Ruhr Triennale festival, taking the best of the UK’s cultural production out to international audiences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s partnership of arts organizations like MIF is an essential part of the cultural lif</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e of this country; they both contribute to the commissions, the stuff of the Fest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ival itself, and reflect it out locally, nationally and internationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in their varied and thoughtful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">progra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s comprehensive coverage allows the ‘live’ Festiva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l audience, around 250,000 in 2013, to be amplified many times over. In-depth arts programming like Imagine and the Culture Show has given a much wider audience access both to high concept, internationally significant shows like the Damon Albarn/Jamie Hewl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ett/Chen Shi Zheng opera Monkey: Journey to the West, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">productions with a real local and historical resonance, such as Maxine Peake’s Masque of Anarchy. Crucially, this reflection of the Festival’s work across the BBC’s output</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> broadens our audience subs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tantially and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> makes the Festival’s funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from organisations including Manchester City Council, Arts Council England and dozens of commercial spo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsors and private individuals – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">go much, much further. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In establishing BBC North, the corporation has provided a renewed energy for the cultural sector in the North West. The various BBC teams have built new relationships with local arts organisations and raised the profile of their output nationally – shiftin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g the London-centric nature of the BBC’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cultural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focus significantly.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe the BBC is fulfilling its role and remit with vigour and that by sustaining and deepening its relationships with cultural organisations like MIF it can continue to be one of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the defining features of the UK’s cultural landscape, and an example internationally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>